All patients consistently experienced a progressive and statistically significant reduction in A-a O2 gradient during the study period (Table 2
). After 24, 48 hours and 7 days the A-a O2 was reduced by 33 (41), 52 (29) and 138 (49) mmHg, respectively (P = 0.005), while this trend was not visible for controls at the same time-points (P = 0.047) (Table 2, Fig. 1
and Table S3). Accordingly, in some patients PaO2 increased and administered FiO2 was reduced (Table S1), justifying the observed increase in PAO2/FIO2 ratio of 52 (70), 64 (48) and 108 (57) mmHg after 24, 48 hours and 7 days (P = 0.037) (Table 2). A trend towards an increase in PaO2 and PAO2/FIO2 was present in controls, although it was not statistically significant (Table 2).
